F. The Cottonian Manuscript, Vitellius, A. xiii. (sol. 90, b‚) in quarto, upon vellum, writ- ten about the beginning of the fourteenth century. It is without title or rubric, and omits all previous to the words, ‘Britannia insula a quodam Bruto consule Romano dicta? (ξ 7.) It contains the Genealogies, names of Cities, and Miracles.

G. The Burney Manuscript, 310, (p. 315‚) written upon vellum in solio, in the year 1381. It contains the shorter Prologue, to which it prefixes this rubric: ‘ Incipit Eulogium bre- vissimum Britanniae insulae, quod Nennius Elvodugi congregavit? Between the Pro- logue and the work are these words, ‘ Explicit Eulogium. Incipit Gesta Brittonum a Gilda Sapiente, aut Nennio, composita.' Its mar- gins contain some os the interpolated passages, in which it agrees closely with K. and N. Omitting the Genealogies, it preserves the names of the Cities and the Miracles, to which is appended the rubrio, ‘ Explicit Gesta Britto- num, a Gilda Sapiente composita.'
